g.text: Cookies
Cookies are used to store data on the client side. To view cookies stored in the browser, we can go to the applications tab and then see cookies.
Cookies are nothing but data stored in the form of key and value pairs.
In order to use cookies inside the express app, we need to use the cookie-parser library.
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const cookieParser = require('cookie-parser');
app.use(cookieParser());
In order to set values on a cookie, we can use the res.cookie() method.
Now when we want to use cookies, the cookies are automatically sent along with the request. So we can get access to the value stored
inside the cookies by using the req.cookies object. This object has been provided by the cookie parser library.
Cookie management in the browser
Cookies are automatically sent with every HTTP request to the server, so avoid storing sensitive data directly in cookies unless they are encrypted.
Signing the cookies
these are cookies that include a cryptographic signature to ensure their integrity. Signed cookies are used to verify that the data in the cookie
has not been tampered with by the client.
The signed cookies are stored inside a seperate object provided by the cookie-parser called as req.signedCookies.
{signed: true}
makes the cookie signed
signed cookies are stored inside a seperate object req.signedCookies
However, in order to use a signed cookie, we need to pass in a secret key inside the cookieParser() function during the initialization.
Sessions
Sessions are also key value pairs of data. The only difference is that they are stored on the server side in the server store.
Sessions are very helpful in managing state in stateless protocols like HTTP since HTTP is stateless which means each request
is independent and does not retain information about the previous request.
How sessions work
When the client first sends a request along with the data to be stored, then a unique session ID is created on the server side and the user data
is stored. After successfully storing the user data, the session store then returns a cookie to the client which has a unique session ID as the
value. Now in subsequent request, this cookie is also sent along with the request. The server then validates the value present inside this cookie
and gives the data from the session store.
If this cookie has been tempered in any way, the server would not be able to successfully retrieve the information from the session store.
Thus we can write an overall general set of steps as follows:
1. The client sends a request to the server i.e., the user accesses the website.
2. The session generates a unique session ID and stores user related information inside the session store.
3. The server then sends back a cookie to the client which is then stored inside the user's browser.
4. This cookie is then sent along with each request to the server. Now the server can authenticate the user with this session Id.

Using sessions inside the express JS application
The req.session object can be used to store on the session store
on the server. This would store the data inside the session store
and a cookie would be sent back to client. We can check the cookie
present by checking the application tab inside the chrome dev tools
and looking inside the cookies tab.
Now if we ant to use the session data, we can directly use the req.session
object. The cookie which has session Id stored is also sent with each request.
